{
  "answer": "**This passage appears in Charles Comte's *Traité de la propriété*, Volume I, Chapter 4 (\"On the occupation of things\").**[^1]\n\nThere, Comte ridicules the jurists' (such as Pufendorf) theory that property originated from a supposed universal convention among all humans, renouncing common rights over everything in favor of exclusive claims via occupation. He argues this \"universal right\" is a \"chimera,\" as it would absurdly require global consent for basic acts of survival:\n\n> By what reasoning would one have succeeded in demonstrating to an inhabitant of Peru that he could not pick the fruit that grew at his hand, without infringing upon the rights of the inhabitants of Siberia? How would one have made an inhabitant of Kamchatka understand that he could not clothe himself in the skin of an animal, without injuring the rights of the Arabs? How would one have gone about showing the Gauls that they could not, in conscience, bring the plains of Auvergne under cultivation, without having obtained the permission of the inhabitants of Tibet?[^1]\n\nComte contrasts this with the natural necessity of occupation as the basis for property formation, without needing fictional pacts.\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/04-de-loccupation-des-choses/translation/#p-5f2b15).",
